‚ÄúRealtor here.
Many homes in Shore Acres have flooded 1, 2 and a few even 3 times within the last 18 months. We're at the point now where many have finished repairs and are up and on the market . That is why so many are for sale and many homes now asking in the 300s which was pretty rare in 2023 despite median home price being higher now. This is also true of Riviera Bay which is also equally low if not lower but gets a lot less press.
In all of 2023 there were 5 homes there sold under 300k and only 28 sold under 400k.
Comparatively in just the few months of 2024, we have already matched the 28 homes sold under 400k. And currently 11 sold under 300k, and you can choose from 20 active listings currently under 400k.
The only other time I've seen that wide scale of a neighborhood price shift is when a major golf course closes in a planned community (Walden Lake in Plant City for example).
Nearly as many homes flooded in Eta, but for whatever reason the city and the news didn't really make a big deal out of the flooding and restoration work back then.
After a flood event flippers and cash inventors descend on the neighborhood in droves. So either they or the homeowners patch things up, many don't disclose it was flooded, and put it on the market. If you look through the listings you will find they are all oddly brand new renovations and many disclosures say 'Flooded in Idalia' or other describe water intrustion. I saw one home go through 3 owners in 6 months, all off market except the last one.
Source: Lived there and got flooded in TS Eta in 2020. Went through the tears of losing my house and putting it back together. Also just pulled this data directly from the MLS.‚Äù

No, ChatGPT can‚Äôt directly read or interpret CAD files used in construction. CAD files‚Äîlike DWG, DXF, or other proprietary formats‚Äîare built for specialized design software, not text-based models like ChatGPT. Essentially, they‚Äôre speaking a language that ChatGPT just isn‚Äôt programmed to understand.

That said, if you extract the key data or convert parts of your CAD files into a textual format (think dimensions, materials, notes, or even a simplified description of the design), then ChatGPT can definitely help you analyze or discuss that information. For example, you could ask for a breakdown of design requirements, suggestions for optimization, or even help drafting explanations for stakeholders based on the textual data.

If you‚Äôre exploring AI integration into your workflow, consider coupling specialized CAD processing tools with ChatGPT. One tool could extract and transform your CAD data, and then ChatGPT could help generate insights, documentation, or even recommendations for design improvements. It‚Äôs a bit like having a top-notch translator for your blueprints‚Äîthe design software handles the intricate technical details, and ChatGPT can help you communicate the story behind them.

So while ChatGPT itself can‚Äôt directly dive into your CAD files, there are plenty of creative ways to get the power of AI working for your construction projects. Let‚Äôs innovate and bridge those gaps!

There are indeed some AI-powered tools and platforms that are starting to crack the code on interpreting CAD files‚Äîand the field is evolving fast. While ChatGPT isn‚Äôt built for it, here‚Äôs a quick rundown on what‚Äôs out there:
	1.	Autodesk Forge & BIM 360:
Autodesk‚Äôs ecosystem has been pushing the boundaries with tools like Forge, which can process and extract metadata from CAD files via its Model Derivative API. Although it‚Äôs not ‚Äúreading‚Äù in the human sense, it converts complex CAD data into accessible formats. BIM 360, on the other hand, leverages AI to help with construction project management and analysis by extracting key insights from design data.
	2.	Generative and AI-Enhanced CAD Systems:
Companies like Autodesk with Fusion 360 and Siemens NX have begun integrating AI features directly into their CAD systems. These systems can not only analyze designs for optimization (think generative design) but also flag potential issues before they become costly mistakes. They‚Äôre evolving from mere drafting tools into smart assistants that understand the intricacies of design.
	3.	Specialized Research & Niche Startups:
On the research front‚Äîand in some cutting-edge startups‚Äîthere are AI models designed specifically for 3D geometry recognition, semantic segmentation, and even converting CAD models into BIM or digital twins. These projects often use deep learning architectures (like convolutional neural networks or even graph neural networks) to interpret the geometric and topological data embedded in CAD files.
	4.	Custom Integrations:
Many forward-thinking companies are piecing together AI pipelines where a CAD processing engine (using open-source libraries like OpenCascade or FreeCAD) extracts the necessary geometric and metadata, and then custom AI models analyze the data to predict performance, optimize layouts, or generate reports. This ‚Äúbest-of-both-worlds‚Äù approach allows businesses to tailor the process to their specific needs.

Bottom line? Yes, AI is making strides in the CAD space, but the solutions tend to be specialized and integrated within larger design and project management platforms rather than standalone models that you can simply plug in and ask to ‚Äúread‚Äù your CAD file. It‚Äôs an exciting time if you‚Äôre looking to ride the AI wave in construction and design‚Äîinnovative integrations are already in motion, and the pace is only accelerating. If you‚Äôre in the market to adopt such technologies, keeping an eye on these platforms and possibly experimenting with custom integrations could put you ahead of the curve.

In short, while ChatGPT isn‚Äôt your CAD-reading buddy, the industry is definitely moving toward a future where AI doesn‚Äôt just talk about blueprints‚Äîit understands them. Now that‚Äôs something to build on!

Choosing commitment means accepting your partner exactly as they are, despite their flaws. It means never threatening to leave, even if at times you might want to. It also means caring about your partner‚Äôs pain as much as, if not more than, your own.

As John so aptly puts it, ‚ÄúIf my wife is in pain, my world stops so I can listen to her.‚Äù In a committed relationship, you will both stop the world to try to understand and ease each other‚Äôs pain. This is partly why we get married, and this is partly why we love.

We need each other, and we need to be needed by each other. True commitment is choosing each other over others. Because ultimately, what makes relationships work is the decision to make them work.

There is one step that cascades toward all betrayals. It often happens when things aren‚Äôt going well in the relationship. That step is making negative comparisons between our partner and other real or imagined alternative partners.

We call these negative comps. Rather than nurturing gratitude for what we have with our partner, we nurture resentment for what‚Äôs missing. When something bothers us about our partner, rather than discussing it and getting our needs met within the relationship, we fantasize about another relationship and how we might receive what‚Äôs missing from our current one.

These negative comparisons become a dangerous way of dealing with dissatisfaction.



Many years ago, John had been working with a couple for several weeks. One night, they arrived at their session and declared they were done. John was the sixth therapist they had seen, and as far as they were concerned, therapy was failing.

John was surprised. He had thought their case was going well.

‚ÄúCould you do me a favor?‚Äù he asked. ‚ÄúSince you‚Äôve already paid for this session, would you be willing to stay and help me understand why my therapy has failed for you? I have a commitment to myself to grow from my failures.‚Äù

The couple agreed to stay. John asked them what their weaknesses were.

‚ÄúWe had a huge argument,‚Äù the woman began, but then her husband interrupted to continue the story. ‚ÄúWe went to a party, and I was in the middle of a great conversation with a woman I met there. Then my wife tapped me on the shoulder, like she always does, and said she was tired and wanted to go home.‚Äù

The husband continued, ‚ÄúOn the car ride home, I told her that I had found the woman at the party really attractive, and had really enjoyed talking to her.‚Äù

The wife added, ‚ÄúI got angry and told him to grow up and stop flirting with other women.‚Äù

John then asked, ‚ÄúAnd what were you thinking?‚Äù

The woman hesitated before answering, ‚ÄúI was thinking that I wished I was with a more mature man, and that I could do better.‚Äù

At that moment, John understood why therapy hadn‚Äôt worked.

‚ÄúYou can go now,‚Äù he told them. ‚ÄúI know my therapy isn‚Äôt working. Thank you.‚Äù

The couple was stunned. They asked John what he had learned from their argument that made things so clear.

‚ÄúYou two were in love, so you got engaged, got married, bought a house, and had children. But there‚Äôs no real commitment in your relationship. You‚Äôre always thinking maybe you can do better. You meet a woman at a party and compare her to your wife. You complain, and in response, your wife also thinks she could do better with a more mature man. You‚Äôre not really committed.‚Äù

The husband protested, ‚ÄúEverything I do is for my family! I sacrifice every day. What do you mean I‚Äôm not committed?‚Äù

The wife added, ‚ÄúI take care of everything at home and also have a stressful job


Let me tell you the story of Alice in Wonderland, said John. Alice sees this very unusual rabbit go down a hole and she jumps in with two feet.

Alice sees an unusual rabbit and jumps down the hole with both feet. She has no idea what awaits her. Wonderland is full of challenges, fears, and obstacles, but it‚Äôs also an adventure. Alice doesn‚Äôt hesitate. She doesn‚Äôt wait for a better rabbit. She commits to the journey.

‚ÄúThat‚Äôs commitment,‚Äù John explained. ‚ÄúYou two never did that. You have the trappings of commitment‚Äîmarriage, a house, kids‚Äîbut in your minds, you keep looking over your shoulder, wondering if you‚Äôd be better off with someone else. No therapist can help you until you decide to truly commit.‚Äù

A few months later, John checked on them. They had moved, found a new therapist, and were finally talking about trust, loyalty, and commitment. For the first time, they had a fighting chance.

At some point in your relationship, things will get difficult. Your partner will annoy you, hurt your feelings, or let you down. And in that moment, you might wonder if you chose the right person.

Couples who are truly committed don‚Äôt have one foot out the door. They don‚Äôt entertain the fantasy that someone better is out there. If something is wrong, they talk to their partner‚Äînot complain about them to someone else.

Committing to a relationship requires vulnerability. It means asking:

Will they meet my needs?
Will they be there for me?
Will they be there for me?
Will they love me as I am, or try to change me?
Will they betray me?

When we fall in love, we put our best foot forward. But over time, our real selves emerge‚Äîimperfections and all. The real magic happens when we realize that our partner truly loves us for who we are, not the idealized version of us.

Trust is the oxygen of a relationship. It‚Äôs built in small moments‚Äîshowing up when your partner needs you, listening with empathy, and thinking for both of you, not just yourself

Commitment is built by believing‚Äîand communicating‚Äîthat your partner is precious and irreplaceable. It‚Äôs about magnifying their good qualities and minimizing the bad.

On the other hand, betrayal is nurtured by focusing on what‚Äôs lacking in your partner and convincing yourself that they are replaceable.

	‚Ä¢	What it is: A doctor counts the visible follicles on your ovaries at the beginning of your cycle (typically day 2-5).

	‚Ä¢	What it measures: FSH (follicle-stimulating hormone) and Estradiol on day 3 of your cycle.
	‚Ä¢	Higher FSH = Lower reserve

	‚Ä¢	Still useful: As a secondary data point
